04316nam a22006975i 9780813541143DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20062006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135411437 a10.36019/97808135411432doi  a(DE-B1597)530430  a(OCoLC)1163878089  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPS2350.L5bH37 2006eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a818/.3072221 aLudlow, Fitz Hugh, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Hasheesh Eater :bBeing Passages from the Life of a Pythagorean /cFitz Hugh Ludlow; Stephen Rachman. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2006] 4cÂ©2006  a1 online resource (360 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSubterranean Lives00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tSelected Bibliography -- tA Note on the Text -- tThe Hasheesh Eater -- tExplanatory Notes -- tAbout the Editor 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFitz-Hugh Ludlow was a recent graduate of Union College in Schenectady, New York, when he vividly recorded his hasheesh-induced visions, experiences, adventures, and insights. During the mid-nineteenth century, the drug was a legal remedy for lockjaw and Ludlow had a friend at school from whom he received a ready supply. He consumed such large quantities at each sitting that his hallucinations have been likened to those experienced by opium addicts. Throughout the book, Ludlow colorfully describes his psychedelic journey that led to extended reflections on religion, philosophy, medicine, and culture. First published in 1857, The Hasheesh Eater was the first full-length American example of drug literature. Yet despite the scandal that surrounded it, the book quickly became a huge success. Since then, it has become a cult classic, first among Beat writers in the 1950s and 1960s, and later with San Francisco Bay area hippies in the 1970s. In this first scholarly edition, editor Stephen Rachman positions Ludlow's enduring work as not just a chronicle of drug use but also as a window into the budding American bohemian literary scene. A lucid introduction explores the breadth of Ludlow's classical learning as well as his involvement with the nineteenth-century subculture that included fellow revelers such as Walt Whitman and the pianist Louis Gottshalk. With helpful annotations guiding readers through the text's richly allusive qualities and abundance of references, this edition is ideal for classroom use as well as for general readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aCannabis. 0aHemp. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aRachman, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813541143423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813541143.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK